To start a new process, with a twist in the tale:
A file descriptor, as bridge so fine,
Connected to input and output, Morosini!

 hitch a ride on `fork()`'s gentle breeze,
Then through `exec()`, a new task it pleases.
With `dup2()`'s art, a link it weaves,
Binding stdin, stdout to this new leaves.

```cpp
#include <unistd.h>
#include <sys/types.h>
#include <sys/wait.h>
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    int fd[2];
    pipe(fd); // Create a pipe

    pid_t pid = fork(); // Fork a new process

    if (pid == -1) {
        std::cerr << "Fork failed" << std::endl;
        return 1;
    } else if (pid == 0) { // Child process
        close(fd[1]); // Close unused write end
        dup2(fd[0], STDIN_FILENO); // Redirect stdin
        dup2(fd[0], STDOUT_FILENO); // Redirect stdout
        close(fd[0]); // Close the now-duplicated descriptors

        execlp("ls", "ls", "-l", NULL); // Execute a command
        std::cerr << "Exec failed" << std::endl;
        _exit(1); // Exit if exec fails
    } else { // Parent process
        close(fd[0]); // Close unused read end
        std::cout << "Parent process" << std::endl;
        wait(NULL); // Wait for child to finish
    }

    return 0;
}
```

Here, child and parent, a dance they do,
With descriptors linked, a new task ensues.
In C++, where logic and art entwine,
A process born, as stdin and stdout align.
